GM calls new pickup trucks in the United States to repair the seat backrest back
General Motors call almost 19,000 of its new 2014 Chevrolet Silverado and GMC Sierra pickup trucks with built back to fix a problem with manually adjustable seat backrest, a communication of the US vehicle safety regulator on Friday.
Some of the cars it can be a defect in the mechanism for the back of the seat backrest.
For this reason, it does not meet the federal guidelines for vehicle safety in headrests.
"If ascended from the back of the vehicle, it is possible that the hood was not properly protecting the inmates, so there is an increased risk of injury," read the message on the website of the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA).
The recalled models were manufactured between August 1 and September 10.
The delivery of GM trucks began in June and is the most important model launch the insolvency-related restructuring of the leading US car manufacturer since 2009.
GM informed the car owners on the defect in the first half of October.
The NHTSA could not examine because of the 16-day government Shutdowns the notification letters, which had a negative impact on car sales in October.
Sales of the Silverado and Sierra trucks, which were developed for the year 2014, increased by 20% in the first ten months of the year, GM said on Friday.
In October, GM sold 42,660 16,503 Sierra and Silverado pickup trucks.
GM shares rose 1.4 percent to $37.47 on Friday afternoon on the New York Stock Exchange.
